---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Contact | divorcesettlementcalc.com';
const description = 'Contact the divorcesettlementcalc.com editorial team with corrections, feedback, or questions.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Contact</h1>
  <p>Email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We're a small team, so email is the only channel we monitor &mdash; there's no live chat or phone line, and that's by design: divorce settlement questions deserve a considered written answer, not a rushed one.</p>

  <h2>What we respond to</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Corrections to formulas, state classifications, or statute citations.</strong> If a state's property-division regime is misstated, or you've found a citation that's out of date, tell us which page and what the correct rule is. We verify against the primary source before making any change.</li>
    <li><strong>Errors or unclear language in guides.</strong> If a sentence in a guide is ambiguous, contradicts itself, or is just hard to follow, we want to know &mdash; plain language is one of our core editorial standards.</li>
    <li><strong>Suggestions for new content.</strong> If you searched for a divorce-settlement question and couldn't find it on the Site &mdash; a scenario the calculator doesn't handle, a topic we haven't covered &mdash; let us know what you were trying to figure out.</li>
    <li><strong>Press and business inquiries.</strong> Journalists working on family-law or divorce-finance stories, and businesses interested in advertising, can reach the same address.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to expect</h2>
  <p>We read every message. Corrections and editorial questions typically get a reply within a few business days. If a correction is verified, we update the affected page and note the date of the material change, consistent with our <a href="/editorial/">corrections policy</a>. We don't always reply to content suggestions individually, but we do track them for future guides.</p>

  <h2>What we don't respond to</h2>
  <p>We can't evaluate your specific divorce, review your settlement numbers, or tell you what a judge or mediator is likely to order in your case &mdash; that requires a licensed family-law attorney who can see your full financial picture and knows your court's local practice. We also don't recommend specific attorneys, mediators, or divorce-finance products, and we don't accept payment to feature or promote anyone on the Site. If you email us asking for case-specific advice, we'll point you back to this policy and to the guidance below.</p>

  <h2>Before you email</h2>
  <p>Many questions we get are already answered on the Site: check the <a href="/faq/">FAQ</a> for common questions on community property, retirement accounts, and QDRO basics, or the <a href="/guides/">guides</a> &mdash; including <a href="/guides/how-divorce-asset-division-works/">how divorce asset division works</a>, our <a href="/guides/spousal-support-guide/">spousal support guide</a>, <a href="/guides/what-to-do-during-divorce/">what to do during divorce</a>, and <a href="/guides/divorce-settlement-misconceptions/">common divorce settlement misconceptions</a>. If your question is about how the calculator arrived at a number, the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> walks through the formulas and worked examples in detail.</p>

  <h2>If you actually need an attorney</h2>
  <p>We don't make referrals, but a few things are worth knowing before you search. If your divorce is largely amicable &mdash; you and your spouse broadly agree on how to divide things and mainly need help formalizing it &mdash; mediation is often faster and cheaper than litigation, and a good mediator can still flag issues, like an undervalued pension or an overlooked tax consequence, that neither spouse would have caught alone. If there's a real dispute over assets, custody, or support, or if there's a power imbalance, hidden assets, or a history of financial control in the relationship, you're better served by your own family-law attorney rather than mediation alone. Either way, look for someone who actually practices family law and divorce, not a general-practice attorney handling it as a side matter &mdash; property division involving a business, stock options, or retirement accounts benefits from someone who has actually valued and divided those assets before. Most family-law attorneys offer an initial consultation at a modest flat fee or for free, and many mediators charge less than the combined hourly rate of two separate litigation attorneys, so cost alone shouldn't determine which path you pick. If you'd rather start from a neutral referral source, your state bar association's lawyer referral service can point you to family-law attorneys in your area, and many state courts maintain a roster of approved divorce mediators as well.</p>
</BaseLayout>
